MALARIA, AUTOCHTHONOUS - SINGAPORE
**********************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Wed 29 Jul 2009
Source: The Strait Times [edited]
<http://www.straitstimes.com/Breaking%2BNews/Singapore/Story/STIStory_409802.html>
and Ministry of Health, Singapore [edited]
<http://www.moh.gov.sg/mohcorp/pressreleases.aspx?id=22682>


Outbreak of suspected vivax malaria continues to spread in Singapore
--------------------------------------------------------------------
The Ministry of Health (MOH) is currently
investigating a 3rd malaria cluster involving 4
cases of suspected local transmission, near a row
of shophouses located at the junction of
Sembawang Road and Admiralty Road East. The 1st
case is a 24-year-old Singaporean woman who works
in the area. Her illness started on 30 Jun 2009
and she was admitted to hospital on 20 Jul 2009.
She does not have any recent travel history or past history of malaria.

The 2nd and 3rd cases involve colleagues -- a
49-year-old Singaporean man and a 40-year-old
Singaporean woman. They had frequented a
coffeeshop at the row of shophouses. The male
patient fell sick on 11 Jul 2009 and was admitted
to hospital 4 days later. His colleague fell ill
on 12 Jul 2009 and was hospitalised on 17 Jul
2009. The 4th case is a 24-year-old male foreign
worker who was picked up during MOH's active case
finding in the vicinity. He stayed at a nursery
beside the row of shophouses and 1st had symptoms
on 12 Jun 2009. He was admitted to hospital on Tuesday [28 Jul 2009].

MOH said in a statement that the 1st 3 cases have
since recovered, while the 4th case is currently warded in CDC.

This latest cluster is not related to the 2
earlier clusters as none of the 4 cases had
visited Jurong Island or Mandai/Sungei Kadut prior to their illness.

Since the outbreak, MOH has initiated vector
control operations at the site. Larviciding of
potential mosquito breeding habitats and trapping
operations of adult mosquitoes have been carried
out. 13 adult Anopheles mosquitoes were found,
but all tested by the Environmental Health
Institute to be negative for malaria parasites.
Mass fogging of the area too has been carried
out. The NEA is monitoring the situation closely
and will continue with intensive vector control operations.

MOH also is monitoring the situation closely and
will update the public on any new developments.

--
