[3]
Date: 20 Jun 2009, 23 Jun 2009, 16 Jul 2009, 26 Jul 2009
Source: Ministry of Health, Singapore
<http://www.moh.gov.sg/mohcorp/pressreleases.aspx?id=22216>,
<http://www.moh.gov.sg/mohcorp/pressreleases.aspx?id=22284>
<http://www.moh.gov.sg/mohcorp/pressreleases.aspx?id=22562>
<http://www.moh.gov.sg/mohcorp/pressreleases.aspx?id=22630>


Further cases diagnosed from 7 Jun 2009 until 29 Jul 2009
---------------------------------------------------------
One more case of vivax malaria has been confirmed
20 Jun 2009 and added to the malaria cluster at
Jurong Island. He is a 46-year-old foreign
construction worker who works and stays at Jurong Island.

The 23rd case of vivax malaria has been confirmed
and added to the malaria cluster at Sungei Kadut/Mandai Estate.

The 16 Jul 2009 the Ministry of Health confirmed
one more case of vivax malaria. The patient is a
55-year-old foreign construction worker who stays
at Jalan Gali Batu in Mandai and works at the Seletar Camp.

On 26 Jul 2009 one more case of vivax malaria has
been confirmed and added to the malaria cluster
at Sungei Kadut/Mandai Estate. The case is a
21-year-old foreign construction worker who previously lived in Mandai Estate.

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The outbreak has been diagnosed as _Plasmodium
vivax_. Local transmission of malaria in
Singapore was last seen in 2003 (Tambuyah PA.
Singapore Med J
2003;44:336-7,
<http://www.sma.org.sg/smj/4407/4407e2.pdf>;
Fisher D. Singapore Med J 2005;46:596-7,
<http://www.sma.org.sg/smj/4611/4611e2.pdf>), but
the risk of local transmission from imported
cases and asymptomatic migrant gametocyte
carriers constantly exist due to the climate and
presence of local Anopheles vectors. This can
explain autochthonous transmission. It is
noteworthy that the statements from the Ministry
of Health mention that the outbreaks seems to
originate in settlements of migrant construction
workers. If these come from malaria endemic areas
and are asymptomatic gametocyte carrier, this
explains the start of local transmission.

_P.vivax_ can be confused with _P.knowlesi_, a
malaria species present in Macaca irus monkeys
and increasingly found to also cause infections
in humans in Southeast Asia. _Macaca irus_ is
widespread in the Penang peninsula and
_P.knowlesi_ has been reported from Malaysia.

Human infection with _P.knowlesi_ has been found
in Singapore and it was speculated that the
infection came from the numerous free-ranging
monkeys found in the city (Ng T et al. Emerg
Infect Dis. 2008;14:814-6,
<http://www.pubmedcentral.nih.gov/articlerender.fcgi?artid=2600232>).
The authorities have initiated a vector control
campaign by mass fogging. ­ Mod.EP]

[The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of
Singapore is available at <http://healthmap.org/r/00Dc>. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
